{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504499"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:16:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:16:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2336"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2336"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.06,0.59,0.24,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2336"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61518"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2336"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2336"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46969"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"272"},{"type":"tags","id":"646"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"1821"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1190"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1206"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36853"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42469"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43127"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44711"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61518"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old woman has deteriorated while in the Emergency Department. She was treated for gallstone pancreatitis one week ago and subsequently developed acute respiratory distress syndrome requiring mechanical ventilation. After initial improvement, she has acutely deteriorated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears obtunded. Her pulse rate is 125/min, blood pressure 80/60 mmHg, and oxygen saturation 81% despite FiO2 1.0. Her jugular venous pressure is elevated at 12 cm. Chest examination reveals decreased breath sounds on the right side with tracheal deviation to the left. Peak inspiratory pressures are elevated on the ventilator.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pericardiocentesis","Intravenous fluid bolus","Needle thoracostomy","Chest tube insertion","Noradrenaline infusion"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient on mechanical ventilation is now haemodynamically unstable and has deterioration of symptoms with unilaterally decreased breath sounds and elevated inspiratory pressure. She most likely has\u00a0tension pneumothorax\u00a0due to mechanical ventilation. Mechanical ventilation is associated with several complications (e.g., pneumothorax, barotrauma, pneumonia, oxygen toxicity).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA tension pneumothorax is a life-threatening condition where air enters but cannot exit the pleural space, creating a one-way valve effect. This leads to progressive accumulation of pleural air, causing mediastinal shift, great vessel compression, and cardiovascular collapse. The diagnosis is made clinically, with key features including hypoxia, shock, unilateral decreased breath sounds, and tracheal deviation away from the affected side.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeedle thoracostomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the immediate life-saving intervention required for tension pneumothorax in an unstable patient. This involves rapid decompression using a large-bore cannula in the second intercostal space, mid-clavicular line. This converts a tension pneumothorax to a simple pneumothorax, allowing time for definitive management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest tube insertion\u003C/strong\u003E is the definitive treatment but takes too long to perform in an unstable patient requiring immediate decompression. It should follow needle decompression once the patient is stabilised.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericardiocentesis\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for cardiac tamponade, which can present similarly with shock and elevated JVP. Cardiac tamponade presents with a triad of hypotension, distant heart sounds, and elevated JVP. It is not associated with decreased breath sounds or tracheal deviation.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous fluid bolus\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Enoradrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E treat shock but do not address the underlying cause. The obstructive shock in tension pneumothorax requires immediate decompression rather than fluid resuscitation or vasopressors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn stable patients, chest imaging can confirm the diagnosis, but immediate decompression should not be delayed for imaging in unstable patients with clinical features of tension pneumothorax.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tension pneumothorax is characterised by progressive accumulation of air in the pleural space with mediastinal shift, causing cardiovascular collapse","Clinical features of tension pneumothorax include unilateral decreased breath sounds, tracheal deviation, hypoxia and shock","Immediate needle decompression is required for tension pneumothorax in unstable patients, followed by definitive chest tube insertion"],"references":["Zarogoulidis P, Kioumis I, Pitsiou G, Porpodis K, Lampaki S, Papaiwannou A, et al. Pneumothorax: from definition to diagnosis and treatment [Internet]. Journal of thoracic disease. Pioneer Bioscience Publishing Company; 2014 [cited 2021Jan19]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4203989/","Roberts ME, Rahman NM, Maskell NA, et al; BTS Pleural Guideline Development Group. British Thoracic Society Guideline for pleural disease. Thorax. 2023 Jul;78(Suppl 3):s1-s42. doi: 10.1136/thorax-2022-219784. PMID: 37433578."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46969"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2336"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46969"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T16:51:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-24T11:30:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2336"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61518"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"em